Step 6: Consider Format and Duration Alignment
Topic complexity should match your chosen webinar format.

Short-Form Webinars (30-45 Minutes)

Bite-sized webinars work best for tactical, specific topics. "Three Quick Wins to Improve Your Email Open Rates" or "Using LinkedIn for B2B Lead Generation: 5 Proven Tactics" fit this format. They're easy to promote, easier to attend, and generate high completion rates.

Medium-Form Webinars (45-60 Minutes)

This sweet spot accommodates most educational webinars. You can explore a topic with good depth without losing audience attention. Most B2B buying decision topics fit naturally into this window.

Long-Form Webinars (90+ Minutes)

Save extended formats for highly specialized audiences attending for deep expertise development. These work well for workshops, intensive trainings, or expert panel discussions. They attract smaller but highly committed audiences.

Interactive Webinar Formats

Modern audiences appreciate interactive elements. Consider panel discussions featuring multiple experts, Q&A-focused formats where audience questions drive the agenda, or problem-solving sessions where you tackle attendees' specific challenges. These formats reduce the importance of having the "perfect" topic because audience participation drives engagement.

Step 7: Align Topics with Your Service Offerings
Strategic topic selection should naturally position your core services.

If your company specializes in account-based marketing, your webinar topics should educate prospects about ABM value, implementation, and results. If you excel at content syndication for demand generation, your topics should highlight how content reaches high-intent prospects. This natural alignment helps prospects understand how your expertise solves their problems.

Consider your core service offerings and brainstorm topics that let you showcase expertise in these areas. When prospects experience your knowledge firsthand through a webinar, they naturally consider your services when ready to implement solutions.

Step 8: Plan Your Content Series Strategy
Rather than treating each webinar in isolation, consider developing content series that build on each other.

Sequential Learning Series

A series on "ABM Mastery" might include:

Webinar 1: Account-Based Marketing Fundamentals for 2026
Webinar 2: Identifying and Prioritizing Your Ideal Accounts
Webinar 3: Orchestrating Multi-Channel ABM Campaigns
Webinar 4: Measuring ABM Success and Optimizing Performance
Attendees of the first webinar naturally progress through subsequent sessions, creating deeper engagement and better lead nurturing opportunities.

Recurring Topic Rotation

Certain topics worth revisiting annually include industry state-of-the-union updates, annual predictions, and evergreen best practices. Planning an annual webinar series on "Demand Generation Trends and Tactics" provides consistent touchpoints with your audience.

